Based on the results mentioned above, we further developed a PL ratiometric method for the detection of free chlorine. It can be seen that the change of PL intensity is difficult to be distinguished by naked eyes (Fig. S6). It is quite inconvenient for the on-site and on-line detection. Therefore, a small amount of red-emission Ru(bpy)3Cl2·6H2O is mixed with TPA. The red PL signal of Ru(bpy)3
                        2+ is almost inert towards free chlorine. As shown in Fig. S7, when the concentration of the added free chlorine in the mixed solution is increased from 0 to 15μM, the PL intensity of TPA at 415nm decreases gradually, while that of Ru(bpy)3Cl2·6H2O at 618nm is stable. As a result, continuous PL color changes from blue to red could be observed (Fig. 6
                        ).Therefore, a ratiometric PL sensor has been developed, which should be great significant for the on-site and on-line detection of free chlorine.
